.TH DOW 1 "2026-06-25" "dow 0.1.0" "Drift Observation Workbench"
.SH NAME
dow \- track how your AI's behavior changes across versions
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B dow
[\fICOMMAND\fR] [\fIARGS\fR]...
.SH DESCRIPTION
Drift Observation Workbench \- track how your AI's behavior changes across versions.
.PP
Versioning is automatic and Git is a hidden storage backend; you never run git commands. The tool runs fully offline by default.
.SH COMMANDS
.SS init
.B dow init [OPTIONS] [NAME]
.PP
Scaffold a new inference spec (and evals.py) so you can start versioning.
.PP
Creates specs/<name>.yaml from a starter template and, if it does not exist yet,
an evals.py with a couple of example evaluators. Pass a name to choose the spec
(the default is 'summarization'); the spec's name and the file are kept in sync.
Edit the spec to describe your prompt, model, sampling, and evaluation, then run
'dow commit' to capture v1. This only writes starter files \- there is no staging
area, index, or refs, and it refuses to overwrite an existing spec.
.PP
Arguments:
.RS
.TP
.B NAME
Name for the new spec (creates specs/<name>.yaml).
.RE
.PP
Examples:
.RS
.nf
dow init
dow init chatbot
.fi
.RE
.PP
.SS commit
.B dow commit [OPTIONS] [SPEC]
.PP
Run your spec and capture its behavior as a new version.
.PP
Executes every input in the spec and stores the outputs together with the full
runtime capture \- model identity and version, sampling settings, and the resolved
prompt \- as an automatically named version (v1, v2, ...). Run 'dow init' first to
scaffold a spec. Configured evaluators run automatically, and
re\-committing an unchanged spec measures non\-determinism. Use \-\-from to branch from
an earlier version.
.PP
Arguments:
.RS
.TP
.B SPEC
Spec file or name (optional).
.RE
.PP
Options:
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-message, \-m
Short note for this version.
.TP
.B \-\-from
Branch from an earlier version instead of the latest.
.RE
.PP
Examples:
.RS
.nf
dow commit
dow commit \-m "lower temperature"
dow commit \-\-from v1
.fi
.RE
.PP
.SS compare
.B dow compare [OPTIONS] [A] [B]
.PP
Compare two versions: outputs, drift, stability, and a verdict.
.PP
Reports which configuration fields differ, how much the outputs changed, the
semantic drift between the two versions, the stability of each, and an overall
verdict against the spec's thresholds. With no arguments, compares the previous
version against the latest.
.PP
Arguments:
.RS
.TP
.B A
First version (default: previous).
.TP
.B B
Second version (default: latest).
.RE
.PP
Options:
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-spec, \-s
(no description)
.RE
.PP
Examples:
.RS
.nf
dow compare
dow compare v1 v3
dow compare good last
.fi
.RE
.PP
.SS explain
.B dow explain [OPTIONS] [A] [B]
.PP
Explain why behavior changed between two versions (causal attribution).
.PP
Pairs the measured drift and stability change with the exact spec fields that
differ between the versions. If more than one field changed at once, the result
is flagged as confounded, since no single cause can be isolated. Defaults to the
previous version versus the latest.
.PP
Arguments:
.RS
.TP
.B A
First version (default: previous).
.TP
.B B
Second version (default: latest).
.RE
.PP
Options:
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-spec, \-s
(no description)
.RE
.PP
Examples:
.RS
.nf
dow explain
dow explain v1 v2
.fi
.RE
.PP
.SS history
.B dow history [OPTIONS]
.PP
List captured versions and their stability.
.PP
Shows every version in order with its stability score and any tags, and marks
whether your current working spec matches an existing version or is new since the
last commit.
.PP
Options:
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-spec, \-s
(no description)
.RE
.PP
Examples:
.RS
.nf
dow history
.fi
.RE
.PP
.SS inspect
.B dow inspect [OPTIONS] [VERSION]
.PP
Show one version's spec, runtime capture, outputs, tags, and eval scores.
.PP
Prints the full versioned specification, the runtime capture (model, version,
sampling, resolved prompt), the generated outputs, any tags, and saved evaluation
scores. Defaults to the latest version; accepts a version name, last/prev, or a tag.
.PP
Arguments:
.RS
.TP
.B VERSION
Version to show (default: latest).
.RE
.PP
Options:
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-spec, \-s
(no description)
.RE
.PP
Examples:
.RS
.nf
dow inspect
dow inspect v2
dow inspect good
.fi
.RE
.PP
.SS tag
.B dow tag [OPTIONS] LABEL [VERSION]
.PP
Tag a version with a free\-form label (good, golden, baseline, ...).
.PP
Labels work anywhere a version is accepted \- inspect, compare, eval, and so on.
The 'good' label additionally marks the known\-good baseline that 'dow eval'
compares against. Defaults to tagging the latest version.
.PP
Arguments:
.RS
.TP
.B LABEL
Free\-form label, e.g. good, golden, baseline, bad.
.TP
.B VERSION
Version to tag (default: latest).
.RE
.PP
Options:
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-spec, \-s
(no description)
.RE
.PP
Examples:
.RS
.nf
dow tag good
dow tag baseline v1
.fi
.RE
.PP
.SS eval
.B dow eval [OPTIONS] [VERSION]
.PP
Run custom evaluators on a version; compare to the previous and last\-good versions.
.PP
Executes the metrics declared under evaluation.metrics and reports each score next
to the previous version and the most recent version tagged 'good', so regressions
stand out. Results are saved with the version and reused unless \-\-rerun is passed;
evaluators also run automatically on 'dow commit'.
.PP
Use \-\-draft to evaluate your current working spec without committing a version:
edit the spec, run 'dow eval \-\-draft' to see the scores against the previous and
last\-good versions, iterate, and run 'dow commit' when you are happy with it.
.PP
Arguments:
.RS
.TP
.B VERSION
Version to evaluate (default: latest).
.RE
.PP
Options:
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-rerun
Re\-run evaluators even if results are saved.
.TP
.B \-\-draft
Evaluate the current working spec without committing a version.
.TP
.B \-\-good\-tag
Tag that marks the known\-good baseline.
.TP
.B \-\-spec, \-s
(no description)
.RE
.PP
Examples:
.RS
.nf
dow eval
dow eval \-\-draft
dow eval v2 \-\-rerun
dow eval \-\-good\-tag golden
.fi
.RE
.PP
.SS tree
.B dow tree [OPTIONS]
.PP
Visualize how behavior evolves across versions.
.PP
Renders the version lineage as a tree \- the main line as a vertical trunk, with
branches created by 'dow commit \-\-from' off to the side \- annotating each step with
its drift and stability change. Use \-\-mermaid for a Mermaid gitGraph, or \-o FILE to
write it to a Markdown file you can preview.
.PP
Options:
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-spec, \-s
(no description)
.TP
.B \-\-mermaid
Output a Mermaid diagram instead of a terminal tree.
.TP
.B \-\-output, \-o
Write the Mermaid diagram to a Markdown file.
.RE
.PP
Examples:
.RS
.nf
dow tree
dow tree \-o evolution.md
.fi
.RE
.PP
.SS dashboard
.B dow dashboard [OPTIONS]
.PP
Open the web dashboard backed by your live behavior store.
.PP
Serves a local, read\-only dashboard that visualizes the versions you have
captured with 'dow commit': the version tree, per\-version configuration and
outputs, stability and custom evaluator metrics, and drift/verdicts between
versions (computed with the same engine as 'dow compare').
.PP
The dashboard reflects your .dow store live. Capture more versions with
'dow commit' in another terminal and refresh the page to see them. It binds to
localhost only; use \-\-host/\-\-port to change where it listens. Use \-\-export to
write the underlying data as JSON without starting a server. Aliased as 'dow dash'.
.PP
Options:
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-spec, \-s
Spec to display (default: the only/first spec).
.TP
.B \-\-port, \-p
Port to serve on (0 picks a free port).
.TP
.B \-\-host
Interface to bind (localhost by default).
.TP
.B \-\-no\-open
Do not open a browser window automatically.
.TP
.B \-\-export
Write the live data to a JSON file and exit (no server).
.RE
.PP
Examples:
.RS
.nf
dow dashboard
dow dashboard \-\-spec summarization
dow dashboard \-\-port 8080 \-\-no\-open
dow dashboard \-\-export dow\-data.json
.fi
.RE
.PP
.SS help
.B dow help [OPTIONS] [COMMAND]
.PP
Show detailed help for dow or one command (e.g. 'dow help commit').
.PP
With no argument, lists every command. With a command name, prints that
command's full description, arguments, options, and usage examples.
.PP
Arguments:
.RS
.TP
.B COMMAND
Command to explain in detail, e.g. 'commit'. Omit for the overview.
.RE
.PP
.SS man
.B dow man [OPTIONS]
.PP
Output dow's manual page in roff format, or install it so 'man dow' works.
.PP
With no options, prints the man page to stdout \- redirect it to a file or pipe it
into 'man \-l \-'. With \-\-install, writes dow.1 into a man1 directory on your MANPATH
(by default ~/.local/share/man/man1) so that 'man dow' renders the full documentation.
.PP
Options:
.RS
.TP
.B \-\-install
Write the page to a man directory so 'man dow' works.
.TP
.B \-\-dir
Target man1 directory (default: ~/.local/share/man/man1).
.RE
.PP
.SH SEE ALSO
Run \fBdow help\fR or \fBdow help \fICOMMAND\fR for interactive help.
